-- Dana Petroleum's Largest Shareholders Urge Talks With KNOC, Times Reports
-- Thomas Biesheuvel
-- 2010-07-25T11:07:36Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-25/dana-petroleum-s-largest-shareholders-urge-talks-with-knoc-times-reports.html

          
          
             Dana Petroleum Plc’s  largest
shareholder, Schroders Plc, urged the U.K. explorer to negotiate
with South Korea’s national oil company on a takeover offer, the
Sunday Times reported.  
 Black Rock and JP Morgan Asset Management Services Ltd.,
Dana’s second- and third-largest shareholders, support the call
for negotiations, the newspaper reported, without citing where
it got the information.  
 Dana spokesman  Nick Elwes  declined to comment on pressure
from shareholders and reiterated points made by the company in
a July 23 statement.  
 Dana on July 23 said in statement that  Korea National Oil
Corp.  offered 1,800 pence ($28) a share for the Aberdeen-based
company.  
